SIMPLE: refresh
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Refresh
<hw>Re*fresh"</hw> <pr>(r?*fr?sh")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Refreshed</conjf>
<pr>(-fr?sht")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Refreshing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>refreshen</ets>,
<ets>refreschen</ets>, OF. <ets>refreschir</ets> (cf. OF.
<ets>rafraischir</ets>, <ets>rafreschir</ets>, F.
<ets>rafra<?/chir</ets>); pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>fres</ets>
fresh. F. <ets>frais</ets>. See <er>Fresh</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To make fresh again; to restore strength, spirit,
animation, or the like, to; to relieve from fatigue or depression; to
reinvigorate; to enliven anew; to reanimate; <as>as, sleep
<ex>refreshes</ex> the body and the mind</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Foer they have <qex>refreshed</qex> my spirit and yours.</q>
<rj><qau>1 Cor. xvi. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And labor shall <qex>refresh</qex> itself with hope.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make as if new; to repair; to restore.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The rest <qex>refresh</qex> the scaly snakes that fol<?/⟦br⟧
The shield of Pallas, and renew their gold.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To refresh the memory</b></col>, <cd>to quicken or
strengthen it, as by a reference, review, memorandum, or
suggestion.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To cool; refrigerate; invigorate; revive;
reanimate; renovate; renew; restore; recreate; enliven; cheer.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Refresh</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Refresh
<hw>Re*fresh"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of refreshing.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Daniel.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Refresher</ent>⟦br⟧
